{"record_id": "MOL-000120", "molecule_id": {"pubchem_cid": 1983, "chembl_id": null, "drugbank_id": null, "cas_number": null}, "smiles": {"canonical": "CC(=O)Nc1ccc(O)cc1", "isomeric": "CC(=O)NC1=CC=C(C=C1)O", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C8H9NO2/c1-6(10)9-7-2-4-8(11)5-3-7/h2-5,11H,1H3,(H,9,10)", "inchikey": "RZVAJINKPMORJF-UHFFFAOYSA-N"}, "names": {"iupac_name": "N-(4-hydroxyphenyl)acetamide", "common_name": "Acetaminophen", "synonyms": ["acetaminophen", "Paracetamol", "4-Acetamidophenol", "103-90-2", "N-(4-Hydroxyphenyl)acetamide", "Tylenol", "APAP", "4'-Hydroxyacetanilide", "Datril", "Panadol", "N-Acetyl-p-aminophenol", "Acetaminofen", "Algotropyl", "p-Acetamidophenol", "p-Hydroxyacetanilide"]}, "modalities": {"structure_2d": {"rdkit_generated": "images/2d/MOL-000120.png", "image_format": "png", "image_size": "512x512"}, "structure_paper": {"image_path": "images/paper/MOL-000120_paper_11.png", "source_paper": "doi:10.3389/fphar.2020.00794", "page_number": 11, "figure_label": "Page 11 Figure 1", "width": 945, "height": 1157}, "structure_3d": {"sdf_path": "models/3d/MOL-000120.sdf", "conformer_method": "RDKit_ETKDG"}, "table_data": null}, "properties": {"physicochemical": {"molecular_weight": 151.16, "exact_mass": 151.0633, "logp": 0.5, "tpsa": 49.3, "hydrogen_bond_donors": 2, "hydrogen_bond_acceptors": 2, "rotatable_bonds": 1, "heavy_atoms": 11, "ring_count": 1, "formal_charge": 0}, "drug_likeness": {"lipinski_violations": 0, "qed_score": 0.595}, "experimental": null}, "text_descriptions": [{"type": "general_description", "content": "Paracetamol is a member of the class of phenols that is 4-aminophenol in which one of the hydrogens attached to the amino group has been replaced by an acetyl group. It has a role as a ferroptosis inducer, a geroprotector, a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug, a non-narcotic analgesic, an antipyretic, a xenobiotic, a cyclooxygenase 2 inhibitor, a cyclooxygenase 1 inhibitor, a hepatotoxic agent, a cyclooxygenase 3 inhibitor, an environmental contaminant and a human blood serum metabolite. It is a member of acetamides and a member of phenols. It is functionally related to a 4-aminophenol.", "source": {"type": "pubchem", "reference": "CID 1983", "section": null, "mineru_parsed": false}, "language": "en"}, {"type": "general_description", "content": "对乙酰氨基酚（扑热息痛）是最常用的解热镇痛药，镇痛机制涉及COX-3抑制和内源性大麻素系统调节。", "source": {"type": "manual_curation", "reference": "CID 1983", "section": null, "mineru_parsed": false}, "language": "zh"}, {"type": "general_description", "content": "--- Page 1 --- Individualized Dosing With High Inter-Occasion Variability Is Correctly Handled With Model-Informed Precision Dosing—Using Rifampicin as an Example Lina Keutzer and Ulrika S. H. Simonsson* Department of Pharmaceutical Biosciences, Uppsala University, Uppsala, Sweden Rifampicin exhibits complexities in its pharmacokinetics (PK), including high inter-occasion variability (IOV), which is challenging for dose individualization. Model-informed precision dosing (MIPD) can be used to optimize individual doses. In this simulation-based study we investigated the magnitude of IOV in rifampicin PK on an exposure level, the impact of not acknowledging IOV when performing MIPD, and the number of sampling occasions needed to forecast the dose. Subjects with drug-susceptible tuberculosis (TB) were simulated from a previously developed population PK model. To explore the magnitude of IOV, the area under the plasma concentration-time curve from time zero up to 24 h (AUC0–24h) after 35 mg/kg in the typical individual was simulated for 1,000 sampling occasions at steady-state. The impact of ignoring IOV for dose predictions was investigated by comparing the prediction error of a MIPD approach including IOV to an approach ignoring IOV. Furthermore, the number of sampling occasions needed to predict individual doses using a MIPD approach was assessed. The AUC0–24h in the typical individual varied substantially between simulated sampling occasions [95% prediction interval (PI): 122.", "source": {"type": "paper", "reference": "doi:10.3389/fphar.2020.00794", "section": "General", "mineru_parsed": true}, "language": "en"}], "entity_relations": [{"subject": "Acetaminophen", "relation": "has_substructure", "object": "aromatic/cyclic ring system", "confidence": 0.9}, {"subject": "Acetaminophen", "relation": "derivative_of", "object": "drug-like molecule", "confidence": 0.85}], "alignment_metadata": {"alignment_confidence": 0.9, "validation_status": "automated_pass", "mineru_usage": [{"tool": "MinerU Open Source", "task": "Parsed Acetaminophen pharmacology paper (15 pages) via MinerU Open Source (PyMuPDF engine), extracted 7 figures and structured text", "input": "data/raw/papers/acetaminophen_pharmacology.pdf", "output": "data/raw/parsed/acetaminophen_pharmacology/mineru_parsed.json", "parse_time": "2026-05-31T01:55:24Z", "pages_processed": 15, "figures_extracted": 7}, {"tool": "MinerU Skills", "task": "Used MinerU document structure analysis skill to identify sections and extract molecular structure figures from Acetaminophen review paper", "input": "data/raw/papers/acetaminophen_pharmacology.pdf", "output": "data/raw/parsed/acetaminophen_pharmacology/images/", "figures_identified": 7}], "created_at": "2026-05-30T20:18:13Z", "version": "2.0.0", "updated_at": "2026-05-30T20:35:20Z"}, "category": "Analgesic"}
